Awesome Moving Wings

BOM:

1 foam board sheet (100X70 cm)
Hot glue gun + tubes
4 meters of pants rubber (2-2.5 cm width)
2 non woven fabric sheets (110X180 cm)
9 3d printed parts (detailed below)
4 m of 4 mm paracord (550)

Printing The Parts

Print:
4 Top Buckles
4 Top Buckle Pins
1 Center Buckles

Cutting The Wings

Draw 2 of each of the wings drawing above on the foam board sheet. make sure to have enough space for all the 4 wings.
Cut the wings using a utility knife (BE CAREFUL!).

Cutting The Feathers

Draw as many feathers as you can on the non woven fabric.
You can chose their size as you like.
Than, glue the feathers on the wings (hot glue recommended).

Connecting The Printed Parts

Insert a "Top Buckle Pin" in each hole of the wings which is not on the tip of it.
Put some hot glue on the tip of the pin and insert it into the hole of the "Top Buckle".
NOTICE: BEFORE gluing, make sure that the pin fits the hole. If not, enlarge the hole.

Inserting The Wings On The Straps

Cut 3 straps of rubber which fits around your body.
On the first strap, insert the "Center buckle".
On the second strap, insert the two small wings. Make sure they are in the right direction.
On the third strap, insert the two large wings. Make sure they are in the right direction.

Tying The Straps

Tie the first strap on your waist, such as the "Center buckle" will be on the middle of your back.
Tie the third strap under the armpit, in a way that the "Top Buckles" will each be on the edge of the back.
Tie the second strap between the first and the third, in a way that the "Top Buckles" will each be on the edge of the back.

Connecting The Paracord - Big Wings

In this part you will need help from another person.
Tie the end of the cord to the hole on the edge of one of the upper wings. Insert the rope through the "Center Buckle" and hole it with your hand.
Do so with the other upper wing (with a different piece of cord).

Connecting The Paracord - Small Wings

Hold the upper wings in an open position (with your hands up). Connect another piece of cord to the hole on the edge of one of the smaller wings. Pull the cord to the position you would like it to be while it's open, and tie it to the cord of the big wing on the same side just above the "Center Buckle".
Do so with the last wing (with a different piece of cord).

Doen! closed open

description.text:
About a week ago one of my friends told me that he was driving to SF from SD and he was having issues with mounting his phone on his dashboard. He asked me if I could design a smartphone stand for use while driving (navigation purposes of course), kinda like a dashboard mount used for GPS devices.
I got to work and this is what I came up with. It has an extendable arm that varies in length depending on the dowel insert location, and it can swivel on a 180-deg angle based on the tightening knob.
I am currently printing the parts using a Solido SD300 Pro, a printer that uses thin slices of PVC material to produce the finished product. If you guys have any suggestions as to how to improve the overall design, please feel free to comment =)
Oh and right now this only houses iPhones but I am working on several other smartphone configurations... So hang tight!
This is an OPEN SOURCE project, so if you guys happen to modify any of the parts to accommodate your smartphones then please feel free to share =)

The individual parts have been uploaded, but the non-printable parts like the suction cup, knob, nuts and dowel pin can be ordered online through a distributor website called McMaster-Carr. The part numbers are provided below: KNOB : 59625K42
KNOB NUT : 92815A115
SUCTION CUP : 53535A22
SUCTION CUP NUT : 94812A114
ARM DOWEL PIN : 95648A420 You simply need to type these numbers in the search box and the product should come up in their database with all the necessary specs. Please feel free to use any other distributor site (i.e. Home Depot) for these parts. I also uploaded the specs sheet for some parts that detail their exact dimensions. ENJOY! =)

OpenSCAD script to create an Audi high security key HU66A-P. I created this based on taking measurements from my physical key and using the attached spec sheet, which I acquired from a locksmith.

This key will fit the following cars:

A4, 1996-2001
A6, 1996-2000
A8, 1996-2001
Cabriolet, 2000
S4, 1996-2001
S6, 1998-2002
S8, 1996-2002
TT, 2000-2001

This key has 8 cuts at 4 different cut heights. In order to decode the key, start from the cut furthest from the key blade tip and try to identify the key code. The closer the key is to the groove, the lower the number. For example, the key in the STL file has the code 3,3,4,3,1,2,2,1.

Go into OpenSCAD and enter the number from your decoding. Double-check to make sure it looks like your key.

Some vehicles that use this key have a transponder. My car doesn't have a transponder and the key works just fine in my car. Have fun!

comments.text: Crazy-awesome!  This was probably my sixth or seventh print of all time. I had never even heard of OpernSCAD, yet I discovered your project, downloaded OpenSCAD, grabbed my VW Passat key, made some deductions with a caliper, and had a working backup key within two hours, including print time. I entered my deduced key code, adjusted the key head height to match the blade in order to eliminate the need for supports, sliced the exported .stl with the 15.x.x Monoprice-branded version of Cura that came with the Maker Select v2 my wife got me this Christmas, and printed it in PLA. It fit right in and opened my glove compartment. I got progressively braver, opening the hatch and then the driver door before very carefully cranking the car. With the factory key near enough for the immobilizer to deactivate, it works like a charm. That said, I wouldn't use my PLA version in the ignition more than once. It takes way too much force to crank the car. However, it's plenty durable enough to safeguard against locking your factory key in the car. Fantastic example of the potential that 3d printing holds. Thanks for sharing!

title: Customiser: YAPI - Yet Another Pulley for Idlers (aka "Yay, no more soot")

description.text:
Put together to reduce the amount of black dust and soot, the result of abrasion of Y belt at the idler of my cheap Chinese interpretation of a Prusa i3 Pro B. Traces of belt wear are clearly visible in the enlarged photo.

Divided into two (no bearings) or three (bearings, additional axle chuck / bearings distancer) parts, overhangs are entirely avoided, resulting in an easily printable implementation.

Can be customised to operate with or without ball bearings, however I'm afraid that without bearings, I'd eventually have blue PLA dust instead of black belt soot decorate my printer.

It is possibly now to set values which in their combination don't make sense - only few variables are protected against values which don't result in a feasable item. Especially too large bearings can be a source of amusement, if so inclined.

Presets yield an X axis idler pulley for the Prusa i3 Pro B, with MR74 bearings (4x7x2), and slightly increased barrel diameter to keep the X drive belt just a tad more apart - the default "pulley" (two ball bearings without guard) caused the belt running end (opposite of the standing end, relative to X carriage) to touch the channel which leads the belt through the X carriage, furthermore to rub on the pulley holding bracket. Because of increased barrel diameter I had to replace the screw which holds the X idler against a screw with a flatter head, or the belt would touch the screw head. Finding a better fitting screw wasn't hard, because the original screw head had a high profile.

version history

// 2016oct23,ls v0.0.1 initial version
// 2016oct23,ls v0.0.2 redesign, solving some oddnesses with v0.0.1

Success monitoring

About two weeks after installation, I can conclude that the black soot and belt wear problem of my printer has been solved - there is not a trace of newly worn off belt material now.

description.text:
metal C128D Floppy Lock Plus

Replacement for broken floppy lock on a Commodore C128D (metal version) retro-computer.

Plus stands for the added material surrounding the "half-moon" plug, compaired to the original floppy lock.

The floppy-drive drive should be an 1571 model to fit.
The axis for the floppy mechanics is 15mm long (longer than on 1541-II models for C64)

Best printed in ABS to be strong enough.

Attention:
The inner of the "half-moon" has to be reworked to fit smooth, f.e. by rotary tool.
Don't try to push or force the plug on the floppy mechanics - they may get damaged!!!

Two versions of the lock exist:

1 part lock:
Has to be printed with support (more than one try may be needed to get good results)

2 parts lock:
Can be printed without any support and must be glued together.
Aceton is a perfect glue for ABS plastics.

manual re-working needed!

The inner axis (half-moon-plug) must be re-worked,
cause some material from print can make it to small!
Don't try to press the lock on the floppy-drive without doing this.

Floating Skull

After printing off the skull, top, and handle there is still more work to be done to make your awesome floating skull. First straighten out a coat hangar. Next, mark out a 3-5 inch straight section. This will be the section that will hold the skull up. On either side of the aforementioned section, bend a section of coat hangar into a flat spiral at a 90 degree angle to the straight section. The amount of spiral is not important, as long as it is relatively flat and about the size of a quarter. You may have to mark out about 3 inches to use as the spiral and cut the excess material away. When you are satisfied with the spirals, hot glue one side to the top of the handle and the other side to the bottom of the skull. If desired, paint the handle and wire black to make it less visible. Put a tea candle (make sure it is electric, not an actual flame) inside the skull. Congratulations, you now have a floating skull to scare and amaze your friends with!

Bone Blade

It may be necessary to sand parts of the blade down so that the blade fits into the slot on the bone hilt. You may use hot glue to attach the two together permanently, but it is not necessary.

Shapping the support

After removing from the printer, lightly sand both sides to remove any irregularities. Then place the stiffener inside your cap behind the sweat band and push it into shape with one hand at the front of the cap and the other on the mesh inside the cap. Holding the mesh in the shape desired with your hand outside the cap, pass a heat gun over the mesh for a few seconds until the plastic looses stiffness. Put the heat gun down and slide your fingers along the surface of the mesh to keep it smooth as it cools. The plastic does not need to be hot, just quite warm, so don't overdo the heating.

You can use the support unattached to the hat or use fabric glue to bind it to the inside the hat for a smoother front. I put fabric glue between the hat and the formed support, then folded the hat front back over wadded up plastic bags and used a rubber band around the hat to hold everything in place until dry. Be sure to test the adhesive first on an inconspicuous area to ensure it does not bleed through the fabric.

Since PLA can get brittle after extended exposure to moisture you can prime the plastic to extend the useful lifetime of the mesh.

My 12 gauge Stevens Model 77h shotgun was missing the plug. In Pennsylvania if I want to use the gun for small game it needs the plug to limit the total number of shells the gun can carry to three.

Admittedly you can use something like a wooden dowel to do the same job. This was nice because I did not have to hunt one up and 3D printed stuff is just fun.

In searching online this plug is often called a "duck plug" apparently the federal government requires it for duck hunting as well.

As I said I made this for my Stevens shotgun, but I'm thinking it may work for others. In my gun this seems to work well and doesn't make any rattling sounds.

description.text:
Current Status

Update 10/17/2017
Some of you ask if I could add a ring, so here the result... I made a connor(templar) style ring. Size of the design is ring size 10(62) so dont forget to scale it to your needs (finger) enjoy!

Update 4/9/2017
HI so following comments about issues... I've uploaded fixed part!
-Outer Blade bottom: sorry my bad the latest version was missing the under channel for the rubber band so I re-up the correct version...
-Main Body: I've Re-up the last version that I've print and work... since some people mention me some mesh defect...
-Ratchet Wheel and Gear: Remove rubber band hook on the wheel (historical reason) so it's stronger and easier to print. Also change the radius so more flat space for the pla spring...
-Optionnal Dual Side Inner Blade: Blade design to be printed on his edge (brim recommended) so you could be kick-ass on both side :) ... but harder to print...

Special Thanks to BP94 and Toa_Firox for there respective constructive comments!

Update 1/24/2017
I've just re-uploaded the fixed switchplate (shorter release curve), and removed the ratchet latch (has been replaced by the pla spring ... and it work a lot better)

Update 1/4/2017
Happy New Year :) ! ... I've just added the new design for the ratchet latch... currently in testing but seem to work really nicely!! enjoy!

I've also added a version of the blade latch with no hole... some people have issue to print the original one so i've add a version without the pivot hole...(manual drilling required)... but if you could you should try to avoid using those... normally over a stadard 0.4 nozzle printer those latch print nicely envent at 0.2 layer (0.1 recommended).

Update 11/28/2016
After my weekend's test I've concluded that my prior double hook carriage was a far better design... so i've just updated the stl... (last design was functionnal ... but i've been force to add a drop of hot glue to ensure rubber band stay in place.... this old/ new design was better and work without any help... so this is fixed.

I've been able to assemble a complete working device, some sanding was required... now i start printing the complete design and start documenting assembly...

Update 11/2/2016
Ok, First I've made a thickness calculation error over the latest outer blade top which is now solved.

The double hook latch beat gravity easily! In your Face Gravity! :D... my problem was related to friction against the front stop block... So I've modified the blade to fix that.
The Inner blade double latch work well... but a little weak so I've fix that too...
Fix clearance issue around hook on the switch plate (I was forced to drill a hole next to it to fit the band.... not needed anymore)
I've design a new switchplate double hook carriage that is easier to print and stronger by design, I'm also think of applying same concept over the switch plate itself... could enable a better power adjustment(not sure if its needed... since it currently work very well)

I've also added a new BETA main body low friction edition. would test it over next days...

Change Log:
Fixed Switch Plate.
New Switch plate carriage.
Move Foward the rubber band track on the outer blade so the latch of the blade would be stronger.
Fix some tolerance issue

Incoming:
New Rack Hook design.
Slimmer Ratchet System and slimmer middle plate.
Hole to insert hex nuts to the back for easier assembly/de-assembly.
look to take this design a little smaller...length/width/thickness

Update2 11/2/2016
New Rack Hook design
Ratchet latch tolerance fixed (not yet tested)

MAJOR UPDATE

I've move the main flipper rubber band from bottom to middle plate, this solve the time to time rubber band obstruction, it's now easier to assemble and enable me to slim the system by 2 mm :).

I've also fix the channel for the rubber band on the blade (wider).
Tolerance on blade, latch, rack and gear as been adjusted too.

The only real issue remaining is the join of rubber band an the switch-plate + Carriage... currently it work but require glue to keep them in place ... and the carriage part is hard to print cleanly.
I'm in my way to test 2-3 option: hook on both part, sandwich the rubber band between two part (carriage split in two slim part) ... if you have any other idea feel free to comment :)

I know that I could set the ratchet part to 2mm thickness... And a would probably do it... as soon other issue solved... I would probably be able to take the complete system under 20mm thickness(but since I like the blade as is, it would be hard to go under that...) :)

Update Beta Hook Version
I've just add an hook version of the switch plate.... not yet tested....

Update 27/10/2016
Finally I've found the solution for the rebber band hook of the switchplate...and now i need to found a usage for my ~10 switchplate prototype i've print... lol...

Add gap for flipper in main plate and tune flipper

Update 27/10/2016 part two
I've just added an double hook version of the switch plate... with one hook its hare to find rubber band strong enough to beat gravity so double hook is here :)

* Update 29/10/2016 My fight against gravity**

OK so the previous double hook switch plate wasn't working very well... so here a new version that should fix those issue... the new double hook is design to use a single longer rubber band.

I also modify the blade(inner/outer) to limit resistance and make blade latch easier to print ...

on my way to print and test them,,, hope I would say your face gravity :)

Update 31/10/2016
Fixed the thin wall of the double hook system... looking good to solve the gravity issue :)... if this didn't solve the case, I would slim done a little outer blade to limit weight of the blade... I know using the single hook version with a metal spring work well but my plan is to do the complete thing without any special part... 1 paper clip and couple of rubber band.... that's my plan :)

Original

Since I have an overstock of rubber band, I was looking around for something to complete my medieval vambrace (My Other Designs). I didn't find what a was looking for...(didn't have time for special order of specific spring, special part etc...)

THIS IS A WORK IN PROGRESS!! Currently it seems that some tolerance is too small so it need sanding to make it work... also currently the resulting thinkness of the complete system is a little big in my point of view....

I use smaller air rubber band from dollar store... but it seems that they worn out really fast when use for the main blade extension/retraction... so I keep them for blade latch and Flipper .... but i'm currently reworking the cad to enable the use of something stronger for the blade I've Just updated the Switch Plate and carriage :) (currently rack use standard rubber band which do the job well)

The Switch plate and switchpale latch have Change!!

Special thanks to InDeepPainReborn for his impressive how-to made an hidden blade in wood...this was really usefull and help me to design mine...

Also I'm currently working on another latch system for the main blade...Now working to slim down the model...

Resulting Blade Look Great... I plan to finish the design before Halloween :)

Hope you like it :)

Printer Brand:

Printer:

Tevo tarantula with large bed

0.2

20%

Notes:

Smallest piece (blade latch,switch plate latch,middle plate latch, flipper, other latch) work better printed in 0.1

For a complete 1 arm blade, you need: 1 of the two available body (probably the low friction is the best but didn't completed test yet), 1 of the two available switchplate (for rubber band I recommend double hook ) and 2x sp carriage of the same version ( double hook), 4x main flipper, 2x inner blade latch,2x ratchet latch and 1x all other part.

Getting Started!

Once you've got all needed printed Part, you're alomost ready to go...

Here the list of needed tools and part required:

Rubber band... a lot of them lol(detail: 2 small and strong for the switch plate, 2 ouch-less (or small and weak) for the main flipper, 1 ouchless for the blade latch, 1 ouch-less for the ractchet latch, 1 ouch-less for the middle plate latch and 1 small and not so strong for the rack) . I've buy two pack of elastic band(from a dollar store), 1 pack of Standard (mix size) office elastic band and 1 pack of Ouch-less Style Hair Elastic Band.

1 Medium/small all metal paper clip (I didn't encourage you stealing it from your office!... I couldn't been take responsible of you decision...lol)

Couple of drop of your favourite contact glue... I would prefer not using it but screw wont fit well and high frequency plastic welding at home its a pain lol...

Sanding Stick, sanding paper and/or metal file... die friction, die!

1 pair of pliers (you could succeed without it ... but make the life easier)

Once you've got those, you're ready to go!

Step one: The Blade

Take a deep breath, lets rock!

Part needed for this step:
Inner Blade x 1
Outer Blade top x1
Outer Blade bottom x1

So insert inner blade in outer blade bottom, it must slide loosely inside of it... with no resistance at all! (ok I know its physically impossible so try to reach less as possible...). The inner blade must move easily by gravity force... it must not remain stuck in or out...
If the blade remains stuck... here come to play Sanding tools... rule of thumb: if it stuck, it need more sanding :)... back of the blade, outer blade inner side wall, etc.

Once the blade slide freely, put the outer blade top over it (to enclose the inner blade) with some spare rubber band secure the two outer blade part together (that would lock the inner blade inside the outer blade) and be sure that the inner blade slide freely... if not ...surprise: sand it! until the inner blade slide flawlessly.

Now you have a inner blade that slide ridiculously easily inside the outer blade.... Glue Time!( :( ) remove the temporary rubber band, leave the inner blade inside the outer blade bottom, and put some contact glue on top of the OB-Bottom Wall (be sure to not pour glue on the inner blade) and glue the OB-Bottom and OB-Top around the inner blade. Slide in and out the inner blade until your glue is dry to be sure the the inner blade would not glue to the outer blade.

And now you have a inner blade that slide ridiculously easily inside the glued outer blade :)

Step Two: Inner Blade Latch

Part needed for this step:
Assembled Blade x1 (From Step 1)
Inner blade Latch x2
Small Ouch-less rubber band x1
Medium full metal paper clip
Pair of pliers
(and depending of your print quality you could need to drill clean hole...)

First, Insert a small ouch-less rubber band in the slot that go all around the outer blade, take care that the band must lay flat on the bottom of the slot... no twist.
Now if you look closely at the outer blade you would see small hole going trough the top an the bottom part...(clean them if needed).Cut a strait piece of the paper clip, long enough to fit flush with the bottom of the hole in the outer blade bottom part, all the way to the top of the ob-top part hole.
Take one of the inner blade latch, the rounded extremity should face the bottom of the blade (not the Sharp one) and the installed prior rubber band should fit in the notch of the inner blade latch.
align hole and insert the metal pin you've just cut trough all the three part (OB-Top -> IB-Latch -> OB-Bottom). Be sure that the pin didn't goes out the bottom of the OB-Bottom. You could add a drop of glue on the top of the pin to secure it.
Do those step again with the other latch on the other side of the blade...

The blade is now completed....

Step Three: hey Body!

Part needed for this step:
Assebled Blade x1 (From Step 2)
Main Body x1
Main Flipper x4

First, Clean up the hole in the main body, the flipper should move easily inside of it. Insert the blade assembly inside the body, it should slide freely inside of it. If not, sand the interior wall of the body.
The blade should slide in and out easily under gravity force, From fully extended to fully enclosed. Insert main flipper in their hole, and be sur that they could lock the blade (if not ... sanding... they should lock the blade with no resistance)

Step 4: the switch plate

Small and Strong elastic band x2
Switch plate x1
Switch plate carriage x2

Take the switch plate and insert one of the carriage, clean it (sanding) until it slide freely inside his rail.
Single Hook Version Insert one of the rubber band (or spring) between the hook of the switch plate and the hook of the carriage.
Double Hook Version(recommended for rubber band setup) Hook the rubber band to one of the switch plate hook, stretch it trough one of the hole in the switch plate carriage(far as possible). And you hook it back to the second switch plate hook.
You should have now a switch plate with a carriage that hard to pull out and take is rest place back when release...
Do the same with the other carriage.

Clean up the flat side of the switch plate so it could slide freely inside the top rail of the body (over the blade).

Step 5: Start to looking good :) (aka: assemble blade,switch plate, main flipper and middle plate in body)

Part needed for this step:
Assebled Blade x1 (From Step 2)
Switch plate assembly x1 (from step 4)
Main Body x1
Main Flipper x4

Starting with the main body, insert blade assembly (press the lock latch during insert), Insert the four main flipper in their hole ( the two pin side on top), Put the switchplate (the off center slide opening on the back and cariage pin facing down) and the front blocker(would be glue but not now) on top.

Description

Mount to put a HTC Vive base station on a tent pole so it can be braced against the ceiling for portability.

Materials

  • Foam mat or other padding material
  • 6x M5 screws
  • 6x M5 nuts

Instructions

  1. Print out 1x ClampPlate, 1xPadCap, 2xClampTop
  2. Cut out a 5x5cm square of foam and glue to the top of the PadCap
  3. Mount the PadCap on top the tent pole spike
  4. Clamp ClampPlate onto the upper section of the tentpole using the ClampTop on the top and bottom pairs of holes
  5. Screw the the base station mount onto the ClampPlate
  6. Extend the tentpole upwards to brace on the ceiling

Updates

  • Added recesses for nuts into ClampTop

This is a remake of some wonderful design work over at Inventables https://www.inventables.com/projects/mwp-y-axis-braces and https://www.inventables.com/projects/mwp-y-axis-belt-dust-guards There wasn't any source files so modification wasn't very easy. So I remade it from scratch and narrowed down the materials needed.

If you have a large enough laser cutter you can cut these as one piece. I changed the holes to fit M3 hardware and slotted them so you can move the side rails up/down and flush to the wasteboard.

I also made a front/rear variant that you can use the same braces to hold them in place.

description.text:
Always wanted to make an artistic looking bowl? Well, depending on what you call artistic, you might want to try this. It is a simple bowl, created from 5 triangle shape in a 'circle' where the triangle hight scales down with the circle diameter (factor .65). The elements then are stacked, while making a 7 degree turn on every next stack. Anyhow, I think it just looks nice.

One thing I am not happy with is the connection between layers. I tried matches, but that did not work, and I ended up using tooth-picks (not included). Any suggestions are welcome.

Enjoy building!

Notes:

I used 4mm plywood, but the thickness does not play into it. The holes are 2mm in diameter. Locally sourced tooth-picks perfectly fit.

Assembling the bowl - see illustrative images Assemble the layers by connecting them with a tooth-pick and a little bit of glue. Sand each layer before adding the next one. Mine looked like this. Yes, it could have been sanded more, to get rid of the burn stains, but the layers are only 4 mm so I did not want to be too hard on them. As last step, give it some colour. In my case, a natural colour. Obviously, to ensure best results, the paper cover to keep your table more or less clean need to show vegetables and fruits, no?

Technically, playing around with triangles in Mathematica, then exporting into Illustrator where I added the connection holes. Inspirationally, wanted to try an make one of these and the need for a gift for a friend gave enough motivation to try and play.

title: CVT Transmission: simple, customizable, with reverse!

description.text:
This is a simple (and therefore, hopefully, printable) continuously-variable transmission. The goal here is to print an actual, useable transmission for use in mechanical drive systems.

The concept is: to "shift gears" a friction wheel slides back and forth on a shaft, which changes the circumference at the contact point, and therefore, the gear ratio. (A similar transmission is often found in lawn mowers and snow blowers.)

WORK IN PROGRESS!
This is very preliminary at this point, so don't be too surprised if it doesn't give ideal results yet ;)

Here is a repair video I found that demonstrates how the mechanism works.
https://youtu.be/c4DvnxF7tv8?t=128
(Fast-forward to time 2:08)

Known issues

1) There are no clearance gaps between mating parts
2) Arrangements need to be made for printability.
3) I'm pretty sure I'm overlooking circumradius/inradius math when it comes to faceted shafts.
4) Setting number of sides to 0 should create a round shaft.
5) Need to split the drive wheel into an inner core and a molded silicone tire. (Or o-ring.)
6) Probably more stuff that I'm not considering...

title: The Residents Eyeball Helmet Mask,Top Hat & Cane Topper

description.text:
I have received written permission from The Residents to upload this as an entry to the 2016 Thingiverse Halloween Challenge

I've long been a fan of The Residents. And like every fan I've always wanted to have an eyeball helmet of my very own. The ultimate Halloween costume. Just add a tailcoat tuxedo and go!

This is an involved project. Though it's far from impossible. Some of my parts differ slightly than the current STLs. The STLs present are refined versions, and I what I would use if I were to make another.

There’s also files for a complete top hat, as well as an eyeball if you would like to make a scale model as shown in the pics above.

Non 3D-Printed Parts List:
12" Acrylic Lamp Globe
Hard Hat Harness
Transparent filament in your choice of eye color
Spray paint: Black and in same color as transparent filament
Screws (I used what I had on hand, only three are necessary)
3D Print smoothing compound (epoxy/bondo/etc)
Hot Glue
Super glue
Black See-Through Fabric
2" Black Ribbon
Nylon thread
Tailcoat Tuxedo
Black Walking Stick
Eyeball Cufflinks
White Costume Gloves

Printer Brand:

RepRap

Printer:

Prusa i3 variant

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.3

Infill:

Varies

Notes:

Print the hat with as low of an infill and as thin of walls as possible. The lighter the hat is, the better for your neck and back, as well as assembly.

The iris was done using ~3% infill. The more transparent the iris is the better, I used transparent green Hatchbox filament. The pupil for the cane topper was done in black ABS, but only because it was the only black filament I had on hand. The rest of the parts were made using 25% infill and 4 shells with white PLA from Fargo3D Printing.

Instructions

When painting the iris, cut out a circle of paper slightly larger than the pupil hole and place it over the iris, paint the outer perimeter while remaining perpendicular to the paper. When the perimeter is darkened to your liking, remove the paper and spray indirectly to blend. I used my own eye as a template, so I ran some black sharpie on the reverse side edge, so it just barely shows. I also drew some radial lines on the back to emulate a true eye, this is why it is important to use a transparent filament.

To assemble the hat, print four brim pieces and two top pieces and 10 hat biscuits. Superglue the pieces together. If you have a "3D Printing pen," this is a good time to use it on the back to reinforce the joints. Coat in smoother, sand, repeat. Paint, sand, repeat. Once dry and appears to one's liking, apply the ribbon with permanent double sided cellophane tape. Overlapping as little as possible. The joint between the top and bottom sections is intentionally placed so that the ribbon covers it.

Mask off the sections to be cut out on the globe with masking tape, and draw the desired hole in sharpie. The hole sizes for the hat and pupil are inconsequential as long as they are not bigger than hat and iris. Expanding the head hole will depend on your own head. The holes in the globe were cut using a rotary tool and a cutoff wheel. Take it slow, it will melt, wear a respirator, the fumes are harsh. The globe is also brittle and not consistent in thickness, so be careful. I dropped my first one and it broke. Always store it in the box it came in when not handling it.

To install the pupil, heat up a nail with a torch, and poke about 20 holes around the perimeter of the pupil, about a quarter inch away. Do not drill these holes. The globe will crack. Lay 2-4 layers of ironed out black fabric over the hole, and sew through the fabric into the holes. As you begin to approach the opposite side from where you started, pull the fabric tight, and continue sewing, ensuring the fabric is as flat as possible over the hole. Trim the excess

Hot glue the iris over the pupil. The eye section is done.

Deciding where to mount the harness mounts will depend on your own head. I suggest screwing the back harness mounts to the harness, inserting the harness, followed by your head, and play around where you think it's best. Mark the locations with masking tape. Remove the harness, and hot glue the blocks in place. Once cooled, reinstall the harness.

The front harness mount gets hot glued about where the forehead meets a widow's peak. The forehead stop is screwed into this block and is used to rest the harness on. It's not permanently attached to the harness as the harness needs to rotate as the head is inserted.

The hat mounts need to be manipulated slightly depending on where the hole for the hat was cut. Use a lighter to soften the plastic and squeeze them shut to pinch on the globe rim. The number of mounts is up to you. I used 4 short ones and 2 long ones. Ensure the hat has a nice fit over these mounts.

Hot glue over the mounts, and slide the hat over as quickly and cleanly as possible. This is the most difficult part of this project to do well. If you succeed, give yourself a pat on the back, because you're done.

The cane topper assembly just snaps together. Some sanding may be required.

title: Dasaki Compact 1:3 Geared Extruder for Prusa i3 (MK8 drive gear)

description.text:
Compact (compared to Wade's) geared extruder 1:3. Large wheel has 33 teeth, small has 11. Motor size can range from Nema 17 to Nema 11.
Body_part_B_1_75mm is designed for 1.75mm filament, you have to add a 4mm OD/3mm ID PTFE tube piece.
Body_part_B_3_00mm is designed for 3mm filament, without PTFE tube.
Filament guides named "1_75" are for 1.75mm filament
It allows a clear and nice view of the filament input hole. Includes a filament guide/pressure adjustment mechanism (use some glue to fix the knob to the M4 screw). You can choose four different stiffness for the piece filament_guide.
You can also choose the position of the motor: to the left or to the right.
No supports needed, the supports are included in the 3D models.
Body_part_A and body_part_B include space for extra M3 captive nuts, so you can attach your own stuff like fan ducts, leveling sensors, etc.

You will need a hobbed Drive Gear (MK8 with approx. 7mm effective diameter, for MK7 drive gear see: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1814711) and the following hardware:

2x 605 bearings
1x 623 bearing
1x M5x45mm screw, hexagonal head
1x M5 auto-locking (nylon) nut
2x M5 washers
1x M4x10mm screw, hexagonal head (knob)
1x M4 nut (knob holder)
3x M3x10mm screws (motor)
3x M3x25mm screws (assembly)
4x M3 nuts (2 assembly and 2 pinion)

In 1907 the Humane Society erected a fountain for the benefit of horses and animals to use at the corner of 8th & N Phillips Ave in downtown Sioux Falls. The fountain takes the form of a circular pool with a large bowl at its center and surmounted by a tall square block. On each face of the block is a bronze lion head with a fountain tap that pours water from the mouth. The fountain has become one of the cherished local landmarks and is a popular backdrop for photos.

I used an LG G4 phone with the native camera app. I prefer to use the raw / DNG file format as it gives me the maximum latitude to adjust the photographs at home for maximum use.

I took a total of 14 photographs from various angles capturing as much as possible of the lion. There were a few small spots I still missed, but I wasn't aware of it until after I had finished the model.

When I took the photographs, it was late in the day and the lion face I chose to photograph was shaded so it wouldn't have any harsh shadows or highlights.

Once I came home, I imported the raw / DNG files into Adobe Lightroom and set to work using a homemade camera profile to correct distortions and vignetting. I then carefully evened out the exposures and tones so the photographs would be uniform. I then finally checked each photograph for clarity and sharp details before exporting them as 8-bit TIF files.

I imported the file containing all the photos into Agisoft Photoscan and used the 'High' setting as each step. After creating the sparse cloud, I adjusted the bounding box to fit only as much of the lion face as I could, dumping out the surrounding stonework.

When Photoscan had completed the mesh, I found it was still a bit noisy and had a few small holes at the top of the mane. I exported the model as a OBJ file and opened it in Meshmixer. I carefully smoothed out the worst of the choppy surface along the edges of the lion face then filled the holes.

I still wasn't quite satisfied with the model so I opened it in Remake to finesse it a little more. As a final step, I decimated the mesh down to roughly 125K to keep the details but shrink the model size.

I then imported the cleaned OBJ back into Photoscan and finished the model by adding the texture layer.

Hereby it prevents molten plastic from dripping out of the unused nozzles and onto the printed object and disfiguring the printing result. Before switching to another nozzle, it is first cleaned before being put into the operating range to prevent possible impurities.

Besides using different colors, the Multex4Move offers the possibility to use different materials for the printed object or support structures - with a yet unknown clean printing result. In this manner, printed objects might for example have specfic areas made out of flexible material, while others are made out of stiff material, which offers the possibilities for an incredible amount of printed objects.

In addition, the Multex4Move offers the User unknown possibilities, since even nozzles of different diameters can be used in one single extruder.

title: Gen4 Interface board covers (Top, Bottom, and sides)

description.text:
I don't have side pannels on my interface board, so I created some new top ,bottom, and side plates to keep anything from touching the wires.
Some of these parts are pretty thick, and that's the way it's supposed to be. I want these beefy so they take the impact if I accidentally drop the display or something.

Print, and press in place. remove the bottom two bolts of the interface, press in the bottom cover, and replace the bolts to hold everything together.
Then print both parts of each side (side A and side B are one side, SideAmirror and SideBmirror are the other) and bolt them on using the original side plate mounting hardware
New version coming soon that will have a hinged stand!!!

Turn an old PC power supply to bench power supply withoud modifying it

As you may know, the molex connectors for PC power supply is "normalized" , you will find the same pinout with the same colors.
I pickes banana sockets with the same colors as the voltages available :

Black for ground
Red for +5V
Green for 3.3V
Yellow for +12V
Bleu for -12V

The ON/OFF connects the green wire to ground
The Led is connected between Ground and gray wire (Power ON signal)

This is an ajustable holder for thing:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1562144

Hardware needed:
1 or 2 M6 bolt and nut
2 neodymium magnets 20x10x5mm

This thing is meant to plug into 25mm conduit. It is a tight fit so you might need a hammer ;)
The gaps in the rounded rectangles are 20x10x5mm.
This is the size of standard neodymium magnets. The controller can be pulled loose so you can walk around with it. If you need a longer mount, then also print the "wishbone" file. This creates an extra pivot point en increases the offset from the conduit.

  1. Print basestationmount.stl and put the first magnet in the rectangular slot
  2. Glue the basestationmount on the smart-controller case.
  3. Print the conduitplug and put it in your conduit.
  4. Print the lower mount and put the magnet in the rectangular slot. You might need a boxcutter to shape the slot until the magnet fits tightly
  5. Optional, print the wishbone
  6. Connect the pivots with m6 bolts and nylock nuts.
  7. Increase the tension until the mount stays upright with the smart controller connected to it

title: Z-Axis Mount for Aluminium Extrusion Ultimaker-2 Clone

description.text:
This is a redesigned z-axis mount for the Ultimaker 2 Aluminum Extrusion 3D printer by jasonatepaint. The goal was to increase hole precision for the 340mm rods, and to redesign the top mount for easier mounting and better strength. I removed the middle section of the top piece, so you'll have to measure when mounting.

The mount is designed for 12 mm x 340 mm steel rods. The steel rod holes are EXACTLY 12mm in the drawing without any tolerance. I recommend compensating for overprint by setting the horizontal polygon offset in your slicing software. I used -0.1mm in Cura 2.1.3 (tuned to my printer) which resulted in a very tight fight (a bit of force required to insert the rods) to ensure absolutely minimal movement.

There's no inset for the stepper motor on the bottom like the original part. I also printed the z-extender from AndersV209's modified parts since I have plenty of room, and it increases the z print area a bit.
